## /etc/fstab - Configure auto-mount partitions on boot.
##
## Read https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Fstab for more details.
## PARTUUID robust way for named device, fstab(5) for more details.

## FAQs for Linux Permissions => https://www.redhat.com/sysadmin/suid-sgid-sticky-bit
##
## The command to show the details info of the disk layout is $ ls-disk-layout /dev/nvme0n1
## alias ls-disk-layout='lsblk -o NAME,FSTYPE,FSSIZE,FSUSE%,FSUSED,MOUNTPOINT,LABEL,UUID,PARTLABEL,PARTUUID'

## Disk Partition                               MountPoint    Type    Options                       dump  fsck
PARTUUID=fa02ab0d-0e66-1c45-bbec-d540dd1144a9   /             ext4    defaults,noatime              0     1
PARTUUID=c4efee92-fb3f-2c43-b654-d130f40a430f   /boot/efi     vfat    defaults,noatime              0     2
tmpfs                                           /tmp          tmpfs   defaults,noatime,mode=1777    0     0
## FAQs for SWAP => https://help.ubuntu.com/community/SwapFaq
PARTUUID=b3a01835-8dc9-7f4b-afad-457487970df8   none          swap    defaults,noatime              0     0

## Workspace for codes/docs/dot-files, more shorter path is well and make them sharable between multi-OS
PARTUUID=b1bd84c9-5f41-42fd-85d1-06b3f7c3b5e7   /me           ext4    defaults,noatime              0     0
